<DOC><DOCNO> AP890414-0236 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0237EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     04-14 0817</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0854</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and the Securitiesand Exchange Commission settled a massive civil fraud case thatwill put the junk-bond giant under close federal scrutiny for threeyears and sever its relationship with indicted financier MichaelMilken.   Drexel also announced Thursday that John Shad, a former SECchief instrumental in starting an intense investigation more thantwo years ago that led to the fraud charges, would become itschairman.   The Drexel-SEC pact clears the way for Drexel's previouslyannounced agreement to plead guilty to criminal fraud charges andpay $650 million in fines and restitution to settle another casewith the Justice Department.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush's $90 billion plan to bail outthe savings and loan industry cleared its second majorcongressional hurdle, passing a House subcommittee one day afterreceiving the unanimous endorsement of the Senate Banking Committee.   The 47-member House Banking subcommittee on financialinstitutions passed the bill Thursday by voice vote after fourday-long drafting sessions wading through nearly 200 amendments.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Peter V. Ueberroth's failed bid for EasternAirlines has raised several new possibilities for thestrike-crippled carrier, including an auction run by the federalbankruptcy court and new buyout offers from others.   On Thursday, a day after his $464 million deal with Ueberrothcollapsed, Eastern boss Frank Lorenzo said he is turning attentionto his plan to reorganize Eastern as a much smaller airline.   In Miami, meanwhile, American Airlines chief Robert Crandallsaid American is interested in such Eastern assets as its LatinAmerican and Canadian routes. American, one of Eastern's leadingrivals, already is expanding to capitalize on the embattledcarrier's problems.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texaco Inc. expects to record a $1.3 billionafter-tax profit from the sale of Texaco Canada Inc., companyofficials said.   Texaco's chief financial officer, Allen J. Krowe, told a meetingof securities analysts Thursday that the $1.3 billion would be``slightly offset'' by minor restructuring expenses.   Texaco sold its 78 percent in the lucrative Canadian subsidiaryto Exxon Corp. in January for $3.24 billion. The deal was one ofthe final steps in a massive restructuring following the company'semergence from bankruptcy a year earlier.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The company that publishes the NationalEnquirer, the saucy supermarket tabloid, is being sold for $412.5million in cash to a New York-based concern that publishes romancemagazines.   Macfadden Holdings Inc., whose titles include True Story, TrueConfessions and Modern Romance, said Thursday it was in apartnership that signed a definitive agreement to buy GP GroupInc., which publishes the Enquirer and Weekly World News fromLantana, Fla.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government's report that retail sales rose0.1 percent in March after dropping sharply in February is evidencethat cautious consumer spending is moderating economic growth,analysts say.   Sales totaled a seasonally adjusted $139.42 billion last month,held back by sluggish business at department stores and autodealerships, the Commerce Department reported Thursday. Sales hadplunged 0.6 percent in February.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 28.3 percent rise in early April auto sales mayindicate that cut-rate financing and rebates are attracting buyers,analysts say.   But part of the huge increase reported Thursday also stems fromcomparison with a slower-than-usual sales pace during April 1-10last year.   The eight U.S.-based car and truck makers said they soldvehicles at an average daily rate of 36,967 during early April,compared with a 28,811 vehicle-a-day rate during the same time lastyear.</TEXT><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge temporarily restrainedbillionaire takeover investor Marvin Davis from meddling withunions at Northwest Airlines, which Davis is trying to buy.   U.S. District Judge Harry MacLaughlin granted the temporaryrestraining order Thursday at the request by NWA Inc., parent ofthe nation's fourth-largest airline, saying Davis should avoid any``actions and communications'' disruptive to current contracts orcontract negotiations.</TEXT><DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   ConAgra Inc. said it has agreed to divest aportion of Holly Farms Corp.'s flour milling operation if itsucceeds in a $1 billion buyout of its poultry-industry competitor.   The agreement with the staff of the Federal Trade Commissionwould require ConAgra to divest 2.4 million pounds of Holly Farms'daily flour milling capacity if the merger is completed, ConAgraspokesman Walt Casey said Thursday.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market suffered a broad setback Thursday, as the DowJones average of 30 industrials dropped 23.65 points to 2,296.00.   Bond prices fell, reflecting nervousness about inflation.   The dollar finished lower against major foreign currencies inhectic trading, buffeted by a hike in interest rates by a keyEuropean bank.   Palladium futures prices soared to an 8-year high; platinum andgold futures rose while silver futures were mixed; petroleumfutures plunged; grains and soybeans were mixed; and livestock andmeat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>